    "95516752": {
      "title": "The Effect of Ambient Density on Drop Formation in Sprays",
      "abstract": "Abstract A study has been made of the stability and disintegration of flat sheets produced by single-hole spray nozzles at various densities of the surrounding air. It is shown that a flat laminar sheet injected in vacuo is stable, and that drops are formed only at its edges; the premature break down reported earlier has been found to be due to external causes. At higher air densities the sheet is disrupted by aerodynamic waves and previous theories predicting their wavelength and growth have been extended to show that the form of the controlling equation is critically dependent on the operating conditions; experimental verification is presented for these findings. Theoretical expressions for the size of drops produced from fan spray sheets have also been developed. These demonstrate the surprising result that under certain operating conditions, the drop size increases with ambient density. This prediction has been verified experimentally, the drop size initially decreasing, but passing through a minimum with further increase of ambient density"
    }
  },
